<TITLE> Stocks steam ahead after break </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 5 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks rallied to gains on Sunday after a nine-day closure since Sept. 26 because of Eid vacations. Dhaka Stock Exchange gained on non-bank financial institutions, energy and pharmaceuticals shares but the turnover fell compared with the last trading day although it still topped Tk 4 billion. The benchmark DGEN or general index surged 34.55 points or 1.16 percent to end on 3001.37. The DSI or all share price index finished at 2498.45, down by 11.57 points or 0.46 percent, due to price adjustments of Rupali Bank shares. The blue chip, DSE-20 gained 20.40 points or 0.82 percent to 2486.51. All indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange ended upbeat paced by huge gains in energy, non-bank financial institutions and pharmaceuticals shares. The CSCX or selective categories index increased 70.73 points or 1.20 percent to finish at 5936.44. The CASPI or all share price index closed at 9118.08, gaining 121.40 points or 1.34 percent while the bourse's blue chip, CSE-30 rose 48.45 points or 0.61 percent to 7910.97. Turnover on the DSE was worth Tk 4.50 billion from trading of 30,064,004 shares  edging down from Tk 4.79 billion on Sept. 25, the last trading day before the Eid vacations. The port city bourse witnessed 6,250,698 traded shares with a turnover of Tk 616.727 million from Tk 648.264 million on the previous trading day. Gainers outshined losers on the DSE by 137 to 80 with five issues remaining unchanged. Of the traded 138 scrips on the CSE, 82 advanced and 53 declined, with three static. Atop the turnover board on the DSE was Beximco, which finished at Tk 234.20, up by 8.82 percent. The group's pharmaceutical wing, Beximco Pharma followed up, gaining 5.64 percent to Tk 144.20. Summit Power ended on Tk 827.50, surging 13 percent. State-owned Titas Gas shook off early losses to advance 2.79 percent to Tk 506.25. ACI rose 8.41 percent to finish at Tk 636.20. The other issues on the turnover board  Lanka Bangla Finance, Grameen One: Scheme 2, Keya Cosmetics, DESCO and Power Grid Company of Bangladesh  also rose on buying pressure. bd
